	a <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Ontology> ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Automated change 2025-08-14: GO:0010707 replaced by GO:0001576"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , """Normal CERT Function and Regulation:
Sphingolipids are crucial for membrane structure, signal transduction, and brain development and function, with their metabolism tightly regulated by homeostatic circuits.
The ceramide transporter (CERT) plays a central role in sphingolipid biosynthesis by transferring ceramide (Cer) from the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) to the trans-Golgi membrane, where it is converted to sphingomyelin (SM).
Under normal conditions, when sufficient rates of SM production are reached, CERT is phosphorylated and undergoes a conformational change that inactivates it, leading to its redistribution from membranes to the cytosol. This phosphorylation cycle involves protein kinase D (PKD) initiating phosphorylation at p.S132, followed by CSNK1G2 (casein kinase 1 γ 1) phosphorylating other sites in the serine-rich region (SRR), and the ER phosphatase PP2Cε reversing this action."""^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> ;
	<http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title> "De novo sphingomyelin synthesis with regulation (Human) CerS5 Recon4IMD"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> ;
	<http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/contributor> "https://orcid.org/0009-0002-7487-1936"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> ;
	<http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/date> "2026-05-12"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> .

